article.headline: Baylor 73, Purdue 72
article.story: WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) -- With the momentum in Purdue's favor and overtime seemingly imminent, Brandon McKnight gave the game away. Tim Bush scored a career-high 23 points and Baylor benefited from McKnight's mental error in the closing seconds of a 73-72 victory on Thursday night. Purdue's Bryant Dillon hit a 3-pointer with 4.1 seconds to play to tie the game at 72. But McKnight didn't realize the game was tied and intentionally fouled Baylor's Aaron Bruce to stop the clock. Bruce then made one of his two free throws with 2.4 seconds left to lift the Bears (6-3) to their fourth straight win. Purdue coach Gene Keady's mouth hung open in disbelief as his Boilermakers have now started his 25th and final season at 3-6. "We spend a lot of time in practice working on strategy, telling the kids to know the time and score, know the time and score," Keady said, repeating himself for emphasis. "Evidently that didn't sink in." Carl Landry scored a career-high 29 points and grabbed 10 rebounds for Purdue, which was looking for its first three-game winning streak in almost a year. The last time the Boilermakers won three games in a row was Jan. 25. Despite battling foul trouble, Landry scored 11 straight points midway through the second half to give the Boilermakers a 51-48 lead. But all that was rendered moot when McKnight fouled Bruce. "I was surprised, yes," Bruce said. "The Purdue crowd was amazing. It was deafening and it did get to me when I missed the first one. Fortunately I made the second one." McKnight, a senior and the most experienced member of Purdue's team, couldn't believe his error. "I thought Dillon shot a two-pointer, not a 3-pointer," he said. "I stole his shine from him." It was an impressive performance from the Bears, who have only six scholarship players and were playing in just their second road game of the season. Their first was a 77-43 drubbing at the hands of SMU. "Our first performance on the road was completely opposite of this," said Baylor coach Scott Drew, who coached at Valparaiso before coming to Baylor last season. "Everyone walked away saying, 'I can't believe how tough it is on the road, how intense it is on the road.' Credit the guys for learning from their mistakes." Landry carried the Boilermakers for most of the game, but finally got some help late from David Teague, who finished with 17 points. Teague scored on a fast break layup, then hit a 3-pointer for a 63-62 lead with 3:23 to play. But the star-struck Bush, who also had a career-high 11 rebounds, answered with two huge 3-pointers to lead four players in double figures, including Patrick Fields (18) and Bruce (17). "It was really nerve-racking for me. I was like, 'I can't believe I'm playing at Purdue in front of a legendary coach," Bush said. "It was tough, but it was nice. I loved it." Tommy Swanson scored eight of his 10 points in the second half, including a four-point play and a thunderous tip-dunk during an 11-3 run to give the Bears a 67-63 lead. Dillon scored all five of his points in the final 15 seconds to tie the game, before McKnight put Bruce, an 89 percent foul shooter, on the line. "He's a good kid, he plays his butt off on defense," Keady said of McKnight. "It's a dang shame."
